<div class="mb-requirement-container">
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-14084">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> </span>
      <b>NOTE: </b> The official merit badge pamphlets are now free and
      downloadable
      <a
        href="https://filestore.scouting.org/filestore/Merit_Badge_ReqandRes/Pamphlets/Disabilities%20Awareness.pdf"
        target="_blank"
        >HERE</a
      >
      or can be purchased at the
      <a href="https://www.scoutshop.org/" target="_blank ">Scout Shop.</a>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-9474">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 1. </span>
      Do the following:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-9474 mb-requirement-id-9475">
        (a) Explain and discuss with your counselor the following disabilities
        awareness terms: disability, accessibility, adaptation, accommodation,
        invisible disability, and person-first language. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/Z3faUGgMsNI" target="_blank"
          >We Need to Talk About Disability (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://youtube.com/shorts/X-OecmJeQJ4?si=13PL23LCz6Y0z-M9"
          target="_blank"
          >Disability Isn't a Dirty Word (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://www.nea.org/words-matter-disability-language-etiquette"
          target="_blank"
          >Words Matter! Disability Language Etiquette (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-9474 mb-requirement-id-9476">
        (b) Explain why proper disability etiquette is important, and how it may
        differ depending on the specific disability. Give three examples.
        <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/iG3pQp6HoQM?si=DqAx3LbrAqeH9mDm"
          target="_blank"
          >Disability Etiquette - Respectful Ways to Interact With People With
          Disabilities (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/kLKObHtQmis" target="_blank"
          >Sportable Disability Etiquette (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/bb6uPDwclek" target="_blank"
          >Disability Sensitivity (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/kNMJaXuFuWQ?si=568DA1j2_laLorG_"
          target="_blank"
          >Not Special Needs | March 21 - World Down Syndrome Day (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-9498">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 2. </span>
      Visit an agency that works with people with physical, mental, emotional,
      or educational disabilities. Collect and read information about the
      agency's activities. Learn about opportunities its members have for
      training, employment, and education. Discuss what you have learned with
      your counselor. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
      <a
        href="https://www.tiktok.com/@mychalslearningplace/video/7536333109688569118"
        target="_blank"
        >Mychal's Learning Place (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/7h5oyiKc-B0?si=u__mpN2z99OqYsSf" target="_blank"
        >In Our Own Voice (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a
        href="https://ucp.org/from-concept-to-crag-students-design-adaptive-sports-equipment-to-help-classmate-climb/"
        target="_blank"
        >From Concept to Crag: Students Design Adaptive Sports Equipment to Help
        Classmate Climb (website)</a
      >
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-9477">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 3. </span>
      Do TWO of the following:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-9477 mb-requirement-id-9478">
        (a) Talk with a Scout who has a disability and learn about the Scout's
        experiences taking part in Scouting activities and earning different
        merit badges. Discuss what you have learned with your counselor.
        <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/SvT9gWLe3ds" target="_blank"
          >12-Year-Old Boy Overcomes Disability to Pursue Sports, Adventures
          (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/AQWBun-1KB0?si=5HpZF5OdComSENS1"
          target="_blank"
          >Philmont Scout Ranch: Zia Adaptive Trek (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-9477 mb-requirement-id-9479">
        (b) Talk with an individual who has a disability and learn about this
        person's experiences and the activities in which this person likes to
        participate. Discuss what you have learned with your counselor. <br /><i
          >Resources:</i
        >
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/Okb35sk4KEA?si=oe4DdnaglHhQ7kmr"
          target="_blank"
          >We Asked 5 People With Disability Some Questions Before International
          Day of People With Disability (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/hnKim3S_Pvo?si=fEke9WzADlSMiXo3"
          target="_blank"
          >Kids Ask Questions About Disability (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-9477 mb-requirement-id-9480">
        (c) Learn how people with disabilities take part in a particular
        adaptive sport or recreational activity. Discuss what you have learned
        with your counselor. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/TEC0iEMYs5M?si=pgLu9BDJvQKm9eWH"
          target="_blank"
          >Alison's Story (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/3inIaMOGoXQ?si=LuLQzj_tkQjdTyVz"
          target="_blank"
          >International Day of Persons with Disabilities | Paralympic Games
          (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/L9m84Jc9GX0" target="_blank"
          >THIS is Special Olympics! (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-9477 mb-requirement-id-9481">
        (d) Learn about independent living aids such as service animals, canes,
        and augmentative communication devices such as captioned telephones and
        videophones. Discuss with your counselor how people use such aids.
        <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://www.youtube.com/shorts/EnYivEfJZAg" target="_blank"
          >Walking a Route with my Guide Dog (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://youtube.com/shorts/JOyjBWizTU0?si=c7p4Rn5CnbSImBkz"
          target="_blank"
          >Disability Isn't One-Size-Fits-All: My Mobility Aid Toolkit
          (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/Lqsik6NM5HI" target="_blank"
          >How I Navigate as a Blind Person - 5 Tools I Use to Travel Safely
          (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://www.ada.gov/topics/service-animals/" target="_blank"
          >Service Animals (website)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/ez0x66P97GU" target="_blank"
          >Bridging Apps (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-9477 mb-requirement-id-9482">
        (e) Plan or participate in an activity that helps others understand what
        a person with a visible or invisible disability experiences. Discuss
        what you have learned with your counselor. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a
          href="https://craft.nationaldb.org/OHOA/Module-5/SimulationInstructions_a.pdf"
          target="_blank"
          >Vision Loss Simulation Instructions (PDF)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://youtube.com/shorts/gjp90li7k50?si=tQBY4knOEV9yP5p-"
          target="_blank"
          >Eye Disease Vision Simulator (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/Ezv85LMFx2E?si=t22bJRSC4c_v4by9"
          target="_blank"
          >Amazing Things Happen! (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-9483">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 4. </span>
      Do ONE of the following options:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-9483 mb-requirement-id-9484">
        <strong>Option A—Access.</strong>. Visit TWO of the following locations
        and take notes about the accessibility to people with disabilities. In
        your notes, give examples of five things that could be done to improve
        upon the site and five things about the site that make it friendly to
        people with disabilities. Discuss your observations with your counselor.
        <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/Cok1f-_3ydE" target="_blank"
          >NYC Students With Disabilities Speaking About Accessible Schools
          (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://www.scouting.org/resources/disabilities-awareness/"
          target="_blank"
          >Special Needs Prepared Camps (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-9484 mb-requirement-id-9485">
        (1) Your school
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-9484 mb-requirement-id-9486">
        (2) Your place of worship
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-9484 mb-requirement-id-9487">
        (3) A Scouting event or campsite
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-9484 mb-requirement-id-9488">
        (4) A public exhibit or attraction (such as a theater, museum, or park)
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-9483 mb-requirement-id-9489">
        <strong>Option B—Accommodation.</strong> Visit TWO of the following
        locations and take notes while observing features and methods that are
        used to accommodate people with invisible disabilities. While there, ask
        staff members to explain any accommodation features that may not be
        obvious. Note anything you think could be done to better accommodate
        people who have invisible disabilities. Discuss your observations with
        your counselor. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/qT9LE79Daps?si=cxIIetl8GFwwFC4h"
          target="_blank"
          >Accommodations and Difficulties. (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-9489 mb-requirement-id-9490">
        (1) Your school
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-9489 mb-requirement-id-9491">
        (2) Your place of worship
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-9489 mb-requirement-id-9492">
        (3) A Scouting event or campsite
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-9489 mb-requirement-id-9493">
        (4) A public exhibit or attraction (such as a theater, museum, or park)
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-9494">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 5. </span>
      Explain what advocacy is. Do ONE of the following:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-9494 mb-requirement-id-9495">
        (a) Present a counselor-approved disabilities awareness program to a Cub
        Scout pack or other group. During your presentation, explain and use
        person-first language. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/-uS56z1O46U" target="_blank"
          >The View From Here: My Path to Disability Advocacy | Liam Doyle
          (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-9494 mb-requirement-id-9496">
        (b) Find out about disabilities awareness education programs in your
        school or school system, or contact a disability advocacy agency.
        Volunteer with a program or agency for eight hours. <br /><i
          >Resource:</i
        >
        <a
          href="https://youtube.com/shorts/huwy396lx2c?si=Go8d4I0cZ-BeGmnO"
          target="_blank"
          >Here's How You Can Support People With Disabilities (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-9494 mb-requirement-id-9497">
        (c) Using resources such as disability advocacy agencies, government
        agencies, the internet (with your parent or guardian's permission), and
        news magazines, learn about myths and misconceptions that influence the
        general public's understanding of people with disabilities. List 10
        myths and misconceptions about people with disabilities and learn the
        facts about each myth. Share your list with your counselor, then use it
        to make a presentation to a Cub Scout pack or other group. <br /><i
          >Resource:</i
        >
        <a
          href="http://es.easterseals.com/site/PageServer/?pagename=ntl_myths_facts"
          target="_blank"
          >Myths and Facts About People with Disabilities (website)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-9499">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 6. </span>
      Make a commitment to your counselor describing what you will do to show a
      positive attitude about and toward people with disabilities and to
      encourage positive attitudes among others. Discuss how your awareness has
      changed as a result of what you have learned. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
      <a
        href="https://www.apa.org/ed/precollege/psychology-teacher-network/introductory-psychology/changing-attitudes-towards-disability"
        target="_blank"
        >Changing Attitudes Towards Disability (website)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/r9Y6XMko9Jc" target="_blank"
        >Understanding Disabilities (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a
        href="https://www.silkandsonder.com/blogs/news/keeping-commitments?srsltid=AfmBOoqwXvDqEVi16dK1YUu1UnTilZpMSXAJ35STbVrLDyOcRzM7G5ib"
        target="_blank"
        >7 Ways to Actually Keep the Commitments You Make to Yourself
        (website)</a
      >
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-9500">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 7. </span>
      Name five professions that provide services to people with disabilities.
      Pick one that interests you and find out the education, training, and
      experience required for this profession. Discuss what you learn with your
      counselor, and tell why this profession interests you. <br /><i
        >Resources:</i
      >
      <a
        href="https://bouve.northeastern.edu/news/10-rewarding-careers-for-those-who-want-to-work-with-children-with-special-needs/"
        target="_blank"
        >10 Rewarding Careers for Those Who Want to Work With Children With
        Special Needs (website)</a
      ><br />
      <a
        href="https://www.publicservicedegrees.org/careers/people-with-disabilities/"
        target="_blank"
        >Discover the Best Careers for Helping People With Disabilities
        (website)</a
      >
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
